"""
Context Layer — Ezra chapters 4–7
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-ezra-4-7.py

Key contextual notes:
- Ch 4: Syncretic opponents offer to build, are refused (v3); hired counselors thwart
  plans across multiple reigns; Rehum's letter; 16-year building halt ends at v24
- Ch 5: Haggai/Zechariah restart the work; Tattenai's fair-minded investigation;
  elders confess the exile as divine judgment (v12); "eye of their God" (v5)
- Ch 6: Darius finds Cyrus decree at Ecbatana; comprehensive pro-temple decree;
  temple completed 515 BCE; dedication offering (12 goats for all Israel, v17);
  first post-exile Passover (v19-21)
- Ch 7: Ezra introduced with 16-generation Aaronic genealogy; sōpēr māhîr
  (skilled scribe); Artaxerxes' letter grants extraordinary autonomy;
  Ezra's doxology (v27-28) transitions to first-person narrative
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EZRA_CONTEXT_4_7 = {
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>The adversaries of Judah and Benjamin are the peoples settled in the former northern kingdom by the Assyrians following their deportation of Israel (2 Kgs 17:24-41). These communities practiced a syncretistic religion combining fear of YHWH with worship of their own national gods (2 Kgs 17:33: &ldquo;they feared the LORD but also served their own gods&rdquo;). The text identifies them as opponents (<em>ṣārê</em>, adversaries/enemies) before recounting their approach, signaling their motivations from the outset despite their cooperative-sounding offer.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The offer: &ldquo;Let us build with you, for we worship your God just as you do, and we have been sacrificing to him since the days of Esarhaddon king of Assyria, who brought us here.&rdquo; The appeal to shared worship is historically half-true — they did incorporate YHWH into their religious practice — but theologically false: their worship was syncretic, not the covenant worship of the Torah. The historical reference to Esarhaddon (681-669 BCE) as the king who settled them is archaeologically plausible; Esarhaddon conducted multiple deportation campaigns in the region.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Zerubbabel, Jeshua, and the family heads refuse: &ldquo;You have no share with us in building a house to our God; but we ourselves together will build to the LORD, the God of Israel, as King Cyrus, King Darius, and King Artaxerxes of Persia have commanded us.&rdquo; The refusal is grounded in two foundations: (1) covenantal identity — only the covenant community can build YHWH&rsquo;s house; (2) royal authorization — the Persian decree specified who was authorized to build. The exclusion is not ethnically motivated but legally and theologically defined: legitimate worship requires legitimate standing.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;The people of the land discouraged (<em>mᵉrappîm</em>, weakened, caused to slack) the people of Judah and unsettled them (<em>mᵉḇahalîm</em>, frightened) as they built.&rdquo; The two verbs describe a psychological campaign against the builders: discouragement (weakening of will to continue) combined with intimidation (producing anxiety). The strategy is to make the builders question whether they can succeed rather than to stop them by force. This subtler form of opposition often proves more effective than direct confrontation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>They hire advisers (<em>yōʿᵃṣîm</em> <em>sōḵārîm</em>, counselors for hire) to thwart (<em>lᵉhāpēr</em>, to frustrate, make void) the plans of Judah throughout the reign of Cyrus and into the reign of Darius. The hiring of Persian court officials or lobbyists to work against Jewish interests represents a sophisticated political strategy — not mere local harassment but formal imperial advocacy. The opposition spans sixteen years (Cyrus to Darius), indicating sustained institutional resistance rather than episodic hostility.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A brief notice of Ahasuerus-era (Xerxes I, 486-465 BCE) opposition — a formal accusation filed against the inhabitants of Judah and Jerusalem at the beginning of his reign. This is the only Ezra reference to Xerxes, who is the king of the Esther narrative; the mention establishes that opposition to the post-exilic community was continuous across reigns. The Chronicler situates Esther&rsquo;s story in the background of this ongoing conflict.</p>",
    "7": "<p>In the days of Artaxerxes I (465-424 BCE), Bishlam, Mithredath, and Tabeel write against Jerusalem. The Aramaic section of Ezra begins at 4:8 and runs through 6:18 — the use of Imperial Aramaic (the lingua franca of the Persian empire) for the official correspondence is historically authentic and preserved in the text. The switch from Hebrew to Aramaic marks the transition to official imperial documentation.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Rehum the commander (<em>baʿēl ṭᵉʿēm</em>, master of decree/governor) and Shimshai the scribe compose the formal letter. Rehum&rsquo;s title indicates he is the senior Persian administrative official in Trans-Euphrates; Shimshai is the secretary who drafts the document. Their letter is addressed directly to Artaxerxes, bypassing intermediate administrative levels — they have direct access to the imperial court.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The coalition of petitioners is listed by ethnic/administrative category: Dinaites, Apharsathchites, Tarpelites, Apharsites, Archevites, Babylonians, Susanchites (from Susa), Dehavites, and Elamites — a roll-call of the deported peoples settled throughout the region. The list demonstrates that the opposition has broad multi-ethnic backing, not just local resentment. Each group represents a separate deportation wave from Mesopotamia and Elam.</p>",
    "10": "<p>All the peoples &ldquo;whom the great and noble Osnappar had deported&rdquo; — Osnappar is identified with Ashurbanipal (668-627 BCE), the last great Assyrian king and a prolific deporter of conquered populations. The reference to Osnappar locates the communities&rsquo; origins in the last phase of Assyrian empire-building; these are not recent immigrants but communities established for over a century. The phrase &ldquo;great and noble&rdquo; is ironic or merely diplomatic flattery of a dead king.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The formal letter opening: &ldquo;To King Artaxerxes, from your servants of Trans-Euphrates.&rdquo; The official designation of the administrative province — Trans-Euphrates (<em>ʿăḇar naharāh</em>, Beyond the River) — was the Persian satrapy covering the Levant from the Euphrates to Egypt, including Judah. By identifying themselves as imperial servants writing about the king&rsquo;s interests, the petitioners frame their accusation as loyal service to the empire.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;The Jews who came up from you have arrived in Jerusalem and are rebuilding that rebellious and wicked city.&rdquo; The letter characterizes Jerusalem with two loaded terms: <em>mardāʾ</em> (rebellious, the Aramaic cognate of Hebrew <em>mereḏ</em>) and <em>biʾšāh</em> (bad/wicked). They appeal to Persian imperial records to validate the characterization: the city has a documented history of opposing empire.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The economic argument: if Jerusalem is rebuilt and its walls restored, it will not pay tribute (<em>mindah</em>), tax (<em>bᵉlô</em>), or toll (<em>hălāḵ</em>) — three distinct forms of Persian revenue extraction. The three terms represent different categories of imperial taxation: probably poll tax, income tax, and transit duties. This appeal to imperial economic interests is calculated: Artaxerxes will act not on moral grounds but on fiscal ones.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;Since we are in the service of the palace and it is not proper for us to stand by while the king is dishonored.&rdquo; The petitioners claim the disinterested loyalty of servants who cannot watch the king&rsquo;s interests damaged without reporting. This rhetorical move transforms self-interested opposition into dutiful service. The language of palace service (<em>ʾăḵalnat melaḥ hêḵlāʾ</em>, eating the salt of the palace) is a Persian idiom for imperial employment — they claim loyalty through the metaphor of shared salt.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;Search the record books of your predecessors.&rdquo; The appeal to Persian archival research is historically accurate — the Persian empire maintained meticulous records across its territories, and appeals to the royal archives were standard administrative procedure. The irony is that the same archive system that the opponents invoke to suppress Jerusalem will later be used by Darius to validate the Cyrus decree (6:1-5) and reverse the halt.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;If this city is rebuilt and its walls restored, you will have no portion left in Trans-Euphrates.&rdquo; The maximalist threat: not just reduced revenue but total loss of provincial control. The hyperbole is rhetorical — a rebuilt Jerusalem would hardly threaten the entire satrapy — but the letter is designed to maximize imperial alarm. Effective lobbying requires that the threat sound existential.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Artaxerxes&rsquo; reply is addressed to Rehum, Shimshai, and &ldquo;the rest of their colleagues.&rdquo; The royal response follows the same formal Aramaic epistolary conventions as the letter — the official correspondence protocol is maintained throughout the exchange. The letter is read &ldquo;aloud in full&rdquo; (<em>pᵉrāš</em>, distinctly/clearly) before Rehum and Shimshai, indicating an official reading with witnesses.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&ldquo;The letter you sent has been read aloud in my presence in full.&rdquo; The king confirms he has personally reviewed the document — this is not a bureaucratic response but a royal decision. The personal royal attention to the complaint validates the opponents&rsquo; strategy: they achieved what they wanted, an imperial response based on their framing of the situation.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Artaxerxes orders an archive search and finds Jerusalem has &ldquo;a long history of rising against kings and that rebellion and sedition have been made in it.&rdquo; The search confirms the opponents&rsquo; claims using Hebrew history — the resistance to Assyria under Hezekiah, the vassalage shifts under various kings, the Babylonian conflicts — all recorded in the imperial archives. The characterization is historically selective but not entirely false.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;Powerful kings once ruled in Jerusalem and had authority over all Trans-Euphrates; tribute, tax, and customs duties were paid to them.&rdquo; The Persian records acknowledge the Davidic and Solomonic imperial reach — the empire that collected tribute from the same territory now under Persian control. This is a remarkable acknowledgment: the Persian king&rsquo;s own archives confirm that Jewish kings once exercised regional sovereignty. The argument cuts against the petitioners: Jerusalem&rsquo;s imperial past makes it a precedent, not a warning.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;Issue a command to stop these men.&rdquo; Artaxerxes orders the halt pending further decision: &ldquo;until I give a further order.&rdquo; The &ldquo;further order&rdquo; clause will prove important — it leaves open the legal possibility of resumption. Artaxerxes has not permanently closed the question; he has deferred it. This legal opening is what Darius will exploit when he finds the Cyrus decree.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&ldquo;Be careful not to neglect this. Why should this harm grow and hurt the king&rsquo;s interests?&rdquo; The urgency clause (<em>ʾal tišlû</em>, do not be negligent) reflects imperial administrative concern: a local matter that is neglected can become a major problem. The framing of Jewish building activity as a &ldquo;harm&rdquo; that &ldquo;grows&rdquo; reveals the political calculus: the opponents have successfully convinced Artaxerxes that the temple reconstruction is a security threat, not a religious project.</p>",
    "23": "<p>As soon as the letter is read, Rehum and Shimshai go to Jerusalem and &ldquo;compelled them by force to stop.&rdquo; The Aramaic <em>baʾdrāʿ wᵉḥayil</em> (by arm and force) indicates coercive suppression — the builders are stopped by military or paramilitary means, not merely by legal notification. The speed of implementation (immediately, <em>ʾēdayin</em>) shows how eagerly the opponents had been waiting for imperial backing.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&ldquo;At that point the work on God&rsquo;s house in Jerusalem stopped — and it remained halted until the second year of the reign of Darius king of Persia.&rdquo; The narrative returns to Hebrew at this verse (from the Aramaic section beginning at 4:8). The cessation is placed here narratively but occurred in Artaxerxes&rsquo; reign (long after the Darius-era completion in ch. 6) — the Chronicler has arranged the opposition letters thematically rather than strictly chronologically. The Darius-era resumption (ch. 5-6) is the direct continuation of the Cyrus-era halt of 4:1-5.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>The prophets Haggai and Zechariah begin their ministries — the key intervention that ends the sixteen-year building halt. Haggai&rsquo;s oracle in Hag 1:2-11 confronts the people&rsquo;s rationalizations about why the time is not right to build; Zechariah&rsquo;s visions (Zech 1-8) provide cosmic reassurance and promise. They prophesy &ldquo;in the name of the God of Israel who is over them&rdquo; — in contrast to the letter-writing opponents who spoke in the name of imperial administrative authority, the prophets speak in the name of YHWH himself.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel and Jeshua son of Jozadak — the civil and religious leaders — rise up and resume building &ldquo;with the support of the prophets of God who were with them.&rdquo; The double leadership structure (Davidic governor + Zadokite high priest) supported by prophetic encouragement is the post-exilic covenant community&rsquo;s organizational form. Haggai 1:14 records that &ldquo;the LORD stirred up the spirit of Zerubbabel&rdquo; — the resumption is divinely initiated.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Tattenai the governor of Trans-Euphrates and Shetharboznai arrive to investigate: &ldquo;Who authorized you to rebuild this house and to complete these walls?&rdquo; Tattenai&rsquo;s inquiry is a formal administrative investigation, not hostile suppression. The contrast with Rehum and Shimshai is marked: Tattenai will conduct a fair process, report accurately to Darius, and implement his decision obediently (6:13). He is an honest imperial official rather than a politically motivated opponent.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;We also asked them, &lsquo;What are the names of the men carrying out this building?&rsquo;&rdquo; The recording of names serves both a threatening function (official registration for potential punishment) and a protective one (the names become official records that Darius can verify). In the event, the naming is protective: the builders&rsquo; identities are on record as subject to Darius&rsquo;s investigation, preventing arbitrary suppression while the matter is under royal review.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;The eye of their God (<em>ʿên ʾĕlāhᵉhôn</em>) was on the elders of the Jews, so the officials could not stop them.&rdquo; The divine watchfulness — expressed through the singular &ldquo;eye&rdquo; — creates a window of continuing work. The elders are not stopped while the report goes to Darius because YHWH&rsquo;s attention to their situation effectively suspends the normal administrative process. This is the Chronicler&rsquo;s theological statement on providential protection: the covenant community does not cease its work merely because an investigation is underway.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The letter Tattenai and Shetharboznai send to Darius is reproduced in the Aramaic source (5:7-17). Unlike Rehum&rsquo;s accusatory letter, Tattenai&rsquo;s is genuinely investigative: he reports what he found, includes the builders&rsquo; own account, and asks the king to search the archives. This is administrative fairness: the letter lets the Judean builders speak for themselves and invites royal verification rather than royal suppression.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The formal Aramaic letter opening — &ldquo;To King Darius, all greetings (<em>šᵉlāmāh kōlāʾ</em>).&rdquo; The standard Persian epistolary formula; greetings and health wished to the king before the substance begins. The formal opening signals this is official correspondence, not private communication.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;We went to the province of Judah, to the house of the great God.&rdquo; Tattenai identifies the building as the house of &ldquo;the great God&rdquo; (<em>ʾĕlāhāʾ rabbāʾ</em>) — an honorific Persian officials would use for YHWH, paralleling how they spoke of Ahura Mazda. The description of the building work as using large stones and timbers is archaeologically consistent with descriptions of Herodian and Persian-era masonry.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The question about authorization — &ldquo;Who authorized you to build this house and to complete these walls?&rdquo; — is exactly the question the opponents were hoping would produce a &ldquo;no one authorized this&rdquo; answer leading to suppression. Instead, the builders&rsquo; answer (the Cyrus decree) will vindicate them through the same archive system that Rehum used against them.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;We also asked for their names, so that we could record the names of their leaders and inform you.&rdquo; The administrative scrupulousness of Tattenai&rsquo;s investigation is complete: he records everything — the state of the building, the builders&rsquo; self-description, their names, their claim of royal authorization. The transparency of his report is what makes the case favorable to the builders when Darius reviews it.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The elders&rsquo; response to Tattenai begins with theological self-identification: &ldquo;We are servants of the God of heaven and earth.&rdquo; The universalist title — God of heaven and earth, not merely the God of Israel — is appropriate for a Persian context (cf. Cyrus&rsquo;s decree, 1:2). The elders know their audience; they frame YHWH in terms the Persian official can recognize as referring to the supreme deity.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;But because our ancestors provoked the God of heaven to anger, he handed them over to Nebuchadnezzar.&rdquo; The remarkable confession before the Persian official: the elders attribute the Babylonian exile not to Babylonian military superiority but to divine judgment for their ancestors&rsquo; sin. This is the prophetic interpretation of the exile (Jer 25; Dan 9; Neh 9) stated plainly to a pagan administrator. The theological honesty of the elders&rsquo; response is striking: they do not blame the Babylonians; they own the cause.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The Cyrus decree cited: &ldquo;In the first year of Cyrus king of Babylon, Cyrus the king issued a decree to rebuild this house of God.&rdquo; The title &ldquo;king of Babylon&rdquo; (rather than king of Persia) is Cyrus&rsquo;s legitimate Babylonian regnal title — he used it after conquering Babylon in 539 BCE. The elders cite the most legally compelling form of the decree: the king of Babylon (the kingdom that destroyed the temple) authorizes its rebuilding.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The temple vessels are mentioned — Cyrus gave them to Sheshbazzar (= Zerubbabel, or his predecessor as governor) for return to Jerusalem. The return of the vessels is the physical evidence of the Cyrus decree&rsquo;s authenticity: if the vessels were returned, the decree was implemented. The vessels&rsquo; presence in Jerusalem is material evidence supporting the builders&rsquo; account.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;Cyrus told him, &lsquo;Take these vessels, bring them to the temple in Jerusalem, and let God&rsquo;s house be rebuilt where it was before.&rsquo;&rdquo; The builders&rsquo; account of the Cyrus decree — remembered and transmitted over two decades — matches the decree as found at Ecbatana (6:3-5). The consistency between the builders&rsquo; oral tradition and the written archival record is the crucial verification.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Sheshbazzar laid the foundation of God&rsquo;s house in Jerusalem, and from that time to the present it has been under construction without being completed. The elders honestly admit the incompleteness: the foundation was laid in year 1 of Cyrus (536 BCE) and the building is still unfinished in year 2 of Darius (520 BCE) — sixteen years of interruption. The candor serves them: they are not hiding the building halt, and they have a legitimate explanation for it (opposition, as documented).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The elders ask Tattenai to request a royal archive search: &ldquo;Verify whether Cyrus the king issued a decree to rebuild God&rsquo;s house in Jerusalem.&rdquo; The elders&rsquo; confidence in the archive search is itself evidence of their good faith: they are calling for the very investigation that will vindicate them. They stake their entire case on the existence of a documentary record they may never have seen themselves but believe exists.</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>Darius issues the decree for an archive search. The Persian imperial archive system — spanning the empire&rsquo;s multiple capitals and storage facilities — was one of the most sophisticated record-keeping operations of the ancient world. The search for Cyrus&rsquo;s decree involves looking not just at Babylon (where Cyrus reigned) but at multiple possible locations where official records were kept.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The decree is found at Ecbatana (modern Hamadan in western Iran), the ancient Median capital that served as the Persian summer residence. Cyrus had been at Ecbatana when he issued the decree in 538/537 BCE; official records were kept at the location where the decree was issued. The scroll (<em>gᵉlîlāh</em>) format — a leather or papyrus roll — is the standard archival medium for official Persian correspondence.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The Cyrus decree as found: &ldquo;Let the house be rebuilt, the place where they offer sacrifices, and let its foundations be maintained.&rdquo; The archival version differs slightly from the version cited by the returning exiles in 1:2-4 — the archival version focuses on dimensions and construction specifications (v3-4) while 1:2-4 is a proclamation version for public dissemination. Both are authentic; they represent different forms of the same decree for different audiences.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Specifications: three courses of large stones and one course of timber, with all expenses paid from the royal treasury. The alternating stone-and-timber construction technique is confirmed by archaeological evidence from the Persian period. The royal treasury funding converts the temple rebuilding from a private religious project into an officially sponsored imperial project — changing its legal status entirely.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Furthermore, the gold and silver vessels that Nebuchadnezzar took from Jerusalem are to be returned to the temple in Jerusalem. The explicit mention of the vessels&rsquo; return confirms the correspondence between the oral tradition of the returned exiles (5:14-15) and the written archive: both independently attest the vessels&rsquo; transfer to Sheshbazzar. The legal chain is established.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Darius issues his own decree to Tattenai: &ldquo;Stay away from there. Do not interfere with the work on God&rsquo;s house.&rdquo; The complete reversal of Artaxerxes&rsquo; halt (4:21-23): Tattenai&rsquo;s honest investigation has produced the opposite of what Rehum&rsquo;s hostile accusation achieved. The same Persian administrative system that was weaponized against the builders is now turned to their protection.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;Let the governor of the Jews and the Jewish elders rebuild God&rsquo;s house where it was.&rdquo; Darius grants explicit provincial authority to the Jewish leadership for the building project. The title &ldquo;governor of the Jews&rdquo; (<em>paḥat Yᵉhûḏāyēʾ</em>) is an official administrative designation that recognizes Jewish self-governance within the Persian satrapal system.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Darius goes further: &ldquo;I hereby order what you are to do for these Jewish elders as they build God&rsquo;s house: from the royal revenue of Trans-Euphrates the costs are to be given to these men.&rdquo; Not only does Darius permit the building; he funds it from the provincial tax revenues. The opponents who sought to deny the builders imperial support have inadvertently produced a decision that gives them imperial financing.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Darius orders provision of animals for sacrifice — young bulls, rams, lambs for burnt offerings; wheat, salt, wine, and olive oil — daily as needed, without hindrance. The detail of &ldquo;salt without limit&rdquo; (<em>mᵉlaḥ lāʾ ḥāšᵃḥ</em>) is significant: salt was used extensively in sacrifice (Lev 2:13; Num 18:19; Mark 9:49) and was a government-controlled commodity in the ancient world.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;So that they may offer acceptable sacrifices to the God of heaven and pray for the welfare of the king and his sons.&rdquo; Darius&rsquo;s motivation is explicitly pragmatic piety: he funds Jewish sacrifices to receive Jewish intercessory prayer. The same logic that Cyrus employed (1:2: YHWH charged me) is here expressed more clearly as an exchange: imperial support for temple worship, in return for divine favor on the empire. Persian royal theology accommodated supporting multiple divine cults.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The enforcement clause: anyone who defies this order shall have a beam pulled from his house, impaled on it, and his house made a dunghill (<em>nᵉwalû</em>). The grotesque punishment — being impaled on timber from one&rsquo;s own house, which is then destroyed — is darkly satirical: Rehum and Shimshai tried to stop the building of YHWH&rsquo;s house; anyone who interferes with it will have their own house become an instrument of their execution.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;May the God who has caused his name to dwell there overthrow any king or people who tries to alter this or to destroy this house of God in Jerusalem.&rdquo; The divine name theology (<em>šᵉkān šᵉmēhw tammāh</em>) — the presence of YHWH&rsquo;s name dwelling in the temple — appears in an Aramaic imperial decree. Darius invokes YHWH&rsquo;s self-interest in the temple&rsquo;s preservation as the ultimate guarantee of the decree: YHWH himself will punish violators. This is Solomon&rsquo;s temple-dedication theology (1 Kgs 8:16-20) pressed into service as Persian imperial law.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Tattenai, Shetharboznai, and their associates carry out the decree exactly. The honest administrator&rsquo;s response to royal decision: complete and immediate compliance. The same zeal that had led Rehum and Shimshai to &ldquo;immediately&rdquo; force the halt (4:23) now leads Tattenai to immediately implement the resumption. Administrative efficiency works in both directions.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The elders build and prosper (<em>wᵉṣālaḥ</em>, succeeded) under the prophetic encouragement of Haggai and Zechariah. The building is completed &ldquo;by the command of the God of Israel and by decree of Cyrus, Darius, and Artaxerxes.&rdquo; The combination of divine command and imperial decree is the Chronicler&rsquo;s understanding of post-exilic history: YHWH&rsquo;s purposes are implemented through successive Persian kings, each of whom served the divine will without knowing it as fully as the Chronicler does.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The house is completed on the 3rd of Adar in the 6th year of Darius = March 12, 515 BCE. After the laying of the foundation in 536 BCE (3:10), the sixteen-year halt (4:24), and the four-year second phase of construction (520-515 BCE), the second temple is finally complete. The completion date — twenty-one years after the return from exile — marks the fulfillment of the first phase of the post-exilic mission.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The dedication celebration — Israelites, priests, Levites, and rest of the returned exiles celebrate with joy. The title &ldquo;returned exiles&rdquo; (<em>bᵉnê gālûtāʾ</em>, sons of the exile) becomes the technical designation for the community throughout Ezra-Nehemiah: they are defined by their exile experience and their return, not merely by their tribal membership.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Dedication offerings: 100 bulls, 200 rams, 400 lambs, 12 goats for the sin offering. The scale is a fraction of Solomon&rsquo;s dedication (22,000 oxen, 120,000 sheep; 2 Chr 7:5) — a visible marker of the second temple&rsquo;s humbler glory (cf. Hag 2:3: &ldquo;how does it look to you now? Does it not seem to you like nothing?&rdquo;). But the 12 goats — one for each tribe of Israel — maintain the all-Israel symbolism even though only a portion of Israel was present. The symbolic 12 transcends the actual number.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&ldquo;They appointed the priests to their divisions and the Levites to their courses for the worship of God in Jerusalem, as it is written in the book of Moses.&rdquo; The restoration of Mosaic liturgical order — priests and Levites in their Davidic divisions (1 Chr 23-26) according to the written Torah — is the organizational counterpart to the building&rsquo;s physical completion. The temple is complete when both the structure and the worship community are properly ordered.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The returned exiles observe the Passover on the 14th of the first month (Nisan 14). This is the first Passover in the covenant land since the exile — the feast that commemorates redemption from Egypt is now celebrated by a community that has experienced its own exodus from Babylonian captivity. The calendar correspondence is intentional: the feast of the first exodus is the appropriate occasion for commemorating the second.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The priests and Levites had all purified themselves as a group — &ldquo;they were all ritually clean.&rdquo; The comprehensive purity of the temple personnel stands in contrast to the mixed-purity situation at Hezekiah&rsquo;s Passover (2 Chr 30:17-20), where many came without proper purification. The completeness of the post-exilic purification reflects the seriousness with which the returned community took covenant observance after the exile&rsquo;s lesson.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Passover is eaten by the returned exiles along with &ldquo;all who had separated themselves from the uncleanness of the peoples of the land to seek the LORD, the God of Israel.&rdquo; The Passover extends beyond the strictly genetic Jewish community to include any who have committed to covenant fidelity. The boundary marker is not ethnicity but practice: separation from idolatry plus orientation toward YHWH. This anticipates the later conversion discussions in Nehemiah and is consistent with the OT&rsquo;s broader treatment of the <em>gēr</em> (sojourner) who keeps Passover (Exod 12:48-49).</p>",
    "22": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD had filled them with joy and had turned the heart of the king of Assyria to them.&rdquo; The identification of the Persian king as &ldquo;king of Assyria&rdquo; is the Chronicler&rsquo;s theological shorthand: Persia has inherited the role of the dominant empire (Assyria = the generic imperial power that rules the region); the same God who could turn the heart of Assyrian kings controls Persian kings. The joy of the feast is attributed directly to YHWH: the empire funded the feast; YHWH filled the feast with joy.</p>"
  },
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>&ldquo;After these events, during the reign of Artaxerxes.&rdquo; The temporal gap between the temple&rsquo;s dedication (515 BCE, ch. 6) and Ezra&rsquo;s arrival (458 BCE, ch. 7) is approximately 57 years — the narrator passes over them in silence. The Esther narrative falls within this period (Ahasuerus/Xerxes reigned 486-465 BCE). Artaxerxes I (465-424 BCE) is the king under whom the second major phase of the return occurs. Ezra is introduced with the most elaborate genealogy in the book.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Ezra&rsquo;s genealogy continues: son of Shallum, son of Zadok, son of Ahitub. The name Zadok is the key genealogical credential: the Zadokite priesthood had been the legitimate Jerusalem priesthood since Solomon dismissed Abiathar and appointed Zadok (1 Kgs 2:26-27, 35), and Ezekiel&rsquo;s temple vision reserves the altar ministry for the sons of Zadok (Ezek 40:46; 43:19; 44:15). Ezra&rsquo;s Zadokite descent legitimates his authority as the authoritative interpreter of the Torah.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Amariah, Azariah, Meraioth — the genealogy traces through the post-Solomonic Zadokite high-priestly line. The names overlap with high priests mentioned in the Chronicles genealogies and in Nehemiah 12. The Chronicler&rsquo;s care with priestly genealogies reflects the post-exilic community&rsquo;s need to establish proper credentials for temple service after the disruption of exile.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Zerahiah, Uzzi, Bukki — continuing the high-priestly genealogy. The name Bukki appears in Num 34:22 as the representative of Dan in the land distribution; the priestly line presumably borrowed names from the tribal tradition or shared a common naming pool.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;Son of Abishua, son of Phinehas, son of Eleazar, son of Aaron the high priest.&rdquo; The genealogy reaches its culmination: Aaron, the founding figure of the Israelite priesthood. The 16-generation Aaronic chain establishes Ezra&rsquo;s genealogical credentials more firmly than any other figure in Ezra-Nehemiah. The inclusion of Phinehas (famous for his zeal in Num 25:7-13) in the lineage implicitly connects Ezra&rsquo;s zealous Torah enforcement with his ancestor&rsquo;s covenant zeal.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;This Ezra came up from Babylon. He was a skilled scribe (<em>sōpēr māhîr</em>) in the law of Moses.&rdquo; The Hebrew title <em>sōpēr māhîr</em> (skilled/quick scribe) describes Ezra&rsquo;s professional expertise. In the Persian imperial context, the title would indicate a secretary or official capable of drafting and interpreting documents; in the Jewish context, it specifically designates a Torah specialist. The phrase &ldquo;the hand of the LORD his God was on him&rdquo; frames his expertise as divinely given rather than merely professionally acquired.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Multiple groups accompany Ezra — priests, Levites, singers, gatekeepers, Nethinim (temple servants) — making this a comprehensive reconstitution of the full temple personnel. The Nethinim (literally &ldquo;given ones&rdquo;) are temple servants whose origin is obscure, perhaps descendants of the Gibeonites given as temple servants by David (Josh 9:27; 1 Chr 9:2). The breadth of the returning group signals that Ezra&rsquo;s mission is not merely personal but institutional.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Ezra arrives in Jerusalem in the fifth month of the king&rsquo;s seventh year = approximately August 458 BCE. The fifth month (Av) is the month associated with the temple&rsquo;s destruction (9 Av), making Ezra&rsquo;s arrival in that month a symbolic arrival of restoration during the month of mourning. Whether the Chronicler intends this connection is uncertain, but the post-exilic community would have noted it.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The journey from Babylon departed on the 1st of the first month and arrived in Jerusalem on the 1st of the fifth month — exactly four months. Ezra 8:31 notes that the departure from the Ahava canal was on the 12th of the first month, suggesting the convoy organized at Babylon before departing in mid-Nisan. The precision of dating throughout Ezra-Nehemiah reflects the use of official administrative records as sources.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;Ezra had devoted himself to studying (<em>lîḏrōš</em>) the law of the LORD, to practicing (<em>laʿăśôṯ</em>) it, and to teaching (<em>ûlᵉlammēḏ</em>) its statutes and ordinances in Israel.&rdquo; The three infinitives describe the complete cycle of Torah engagement: investigation of the text → personal implementation → community instruction. The order is deliberate — one must practice before teaching; one must study before practicing. Ezra is not primarily a liturgical official but a Torah scholar whose expertise is textual and pedagogical.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The text of Artaxerxes&rsquo; letter to Ezra is introduced. Ezra is described as both &ldquo;the priest&rdquo; and &ldquo;the scribe, a scholar of the text of the commandments of the LORD and his statutes for Israel.&rdquo; The double title — priest + scribe — is unprecedented in the OT; Ezra holds both cultic and scribal authority. This combination explains his unique mandate: he can interpret the law (as scribe) and enforce it through priestly authority.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;Artaxerxes, king of kings (<em>melek malkayāʾ</em>).&rdquo; The Aramaic royal title — king of kings — was used by Persian rulers beginning with Cyrus. The title&rsquo;s scope claims universal sovereignty; Artaxerxes uses it routinely in official correspondence. The grant to Ezra — from the self-described king of kings — represents an extraordinary delegation of authority: Ezra will effectively serve as a sub-ruler for Jewish religious affairs across the entire empire.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;Any of the people of Israel — including their priests and Levites — in my realm who wishes to go to Jerusalem may go with you.&rdquo; The universal permission for any Israelite in the empire to join the return is a remarkable grant: voluntary emigration from the imperial heartland to a peripheral province, authorized by the emperor himself. The voluntariness distinguishes this from the Cyrus decree (which implied all exiles would return); Artaxerxes authorizes self-selection.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;You are sent by the king and his seven counselors to investigate the situation in Judah and Jerusalem in accordance with the law of your God which is in your hand.&rdquo; Ezra&rsquo;s mission is explicitly investigative: he is to determine whether Judah is living according to Torah. The &ldquo;law of your God which is in your hand&rdquo; likely refers to a physical scroll — Ezra carries an authoritative copy of the Torah as his mandate document. The mission fuses Persian imperial inspection with Jewish religious enforcement.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Artaxerxes and his seven counselors (the seven counselors of Persia and Media who had access to the king, cf. Esth 1:14) contribute silver and gold to the God of Israel. The voluntary royal contribution to the Jerusalem temple follows the Cyrus and Darius precedents; Artaxerxes adds his personal and counciliar gift to the imperial tradition of supporting YHWH&rsquo;s house.</p>",
    "16": "<p>All the silver and gold from the province of Babylon, plus freewill offerings from the people and priests, are to go to Jerusalem. The multiple sources — royal gift, official gift, community freewill offering — mirror the structure of David&rsquo;s temple preparation (1 Chr 29:2-9): king gives first, officials give, people give voluntarily. The pattern of generous covenant giving recurs at each phase of temple building.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Instructions for the funds: buy bulls, rams, lambs for burnt offerings; offer them on the altar of the God in Jerusalem. The imperial funds are explicitly earmarked for sacrifice — not for building or administration — ensuring that the economic support translates into the central covenant act of worship. Artaxerxes understands (or his advisers have ensured) that his funds will produce prayers for his welfare (v10).</p>",
    "18": "<p>&ldquo;Whatever you and your fellow countrymen decide to do with the remaining silver and gold, do it in accordance with the will of your God.&rdquo; The discretionary grant — remaining funds at Ezra&rsquo;s disposal according to divine guidance — gives Ezra extraordinary financial autonomy. This is not mere administrative allocation but genuine theological deference: Artaxerxes grants that YHWH&rsquo;s will (not Persian policy) determines how the money is used.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The vessels given for the service of God&rsquo;s house are to be presented before the God of Jerusalem. The vessels continue to be the material embodiment of the temple&rsquo;s legitimacy: they were taken to Babylon (2 Chr 36:7, 18), returned by Cyrus (1:7-11), and now supplemented by new vessels from Artaxerxes. Each generation&rsquo;s contribution adds to the accumulated covenant inheritance.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;For anything else needed for God&rsquo;s house that you find occasion to supply, draw it from the royal treasury.&rdquo; The open-ended royal treasury authorization is the most generous provision in Artaxerxes&rsquo; letter — an essentially unlimited credit line for legitimate temple needs. The practical limit comes in v22 where specific quantities are set, but the principle of royal treasury backing for temple needs is extraordinary.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Artaxerxes issues a parallel decree to all treasurers in Trans-Euphrates: they are to provide whatever Ezra the priest requests, without delay. The dual authorization — to Ezra and to the imperial treasurers — creates an administrative mechanism for implementation. Ezra has not just royal permission but the active cooperation of the provincial financial apparatus.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Specific limits: 100 talents of silver, 100 measures of wheat, 100 baths of wine, 100 baths of oil, unlimited salt. The limits are generous by historical standards — 100 talents of silver (approximately 3.4 metric tons) is a substantial sum. The unlimited salt provision reflects both the importance of salt in sacrifice and its relative cheapness compared to precious metals. The precision of the decree suggests it was drafted by officials familiar with temple requirements.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;Whatever the God of heaven commands, carry it out faithfully for his house; for why should wrath come upon the realm of the king and his sons?&rdquo; The theological rationale for the imperial support is entirely pragmatic from Artaxerxes&rsquo; perspective: divine wrath is bad for business and dynasty. Yet the practical theology is not dismissed by the Chronicler — YHWH&rsquo;s purposes are served even through self-interested piety. The fear of divine wrath that motivates the imperial decree is still the fear of the right deity.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Tax exemption for all temple personnel: priests, Levites, singers, gatekeepers, Nethinim, and other servants of God&rsquo;s house. No tribute, tax, or toll shall be imposed on them. The comprehensive tax exemption creates a financially independent religious institution: temple personnel are not subject to the normal fiscal demands of imperial administration. This exemption will be contested in Nehemiah&rsquo;s day when opponents infiltrate the temple system.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&ldquo;You, Ezra, using the wisdom of your God that you possess, appoint judges and magistrates to administer justice to all the people of Trans-Euphrates — all who know the laws of your God.&rdquo; Artaxerxes authorizes Ezra to establish a judicial system for the Jewish diaspora throughout Trans-Euphrates — not just in Jerusalem but across the entire satrapy. Those who do not know the Torah are to be taught it. This is an extraordinary grant of semi-autonomous legal jurisdiction within the Persian empire.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Penalties for non-compliance with both God&rsquo;s law and the king&rsquo;s law: death, banishment, confiscation of goods, or imprisonment. The four-tiered penalty system mirrors standard Persian judicial practice. The explicit dual authority — God&rsquo;s law and the king&rsquo;s law — fuses the religious and civil jurisdictions that Ezra represents. Failure to obey the Torah is simultaneously a civil offense under Persian imperial law.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Ezra&rsquo;s doxology: &ldquo;Blessed be the LORD, the God of our ancestors, who put this in the king&rsquo;s heart — to honor the house of the LORD in Jerusalem.&rdquo; The transition from third-person narrative to Ezra&rsquo;s first-person voice marks the shift to the Ezra Memoir that continues through ch. 9. The doxology is the theological response to the imperial letter: Ezra does not see imperial policy as its own cause but as the instrument of YHWH&rsquo;s purpose. The king&rsquo;s heart is moved by YHWH; the letter is YHWH&rsquo;s provision.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&ldquo;He has extended steadfast love (<em>ḥesed</em>) to me in the sight of the king, his counselors, and all his powerful officers.&rdquo; Ezra applies the covenant term <em>ḥesed</em> — the steadfast love of YHWH to his covenant partners — to his experience before the Persian court. The personal experience of divine covenant faithfulness in the imperial context is what motivates Ezra&rsquo;s gathering of leaders for the journey. &ldquo;I took courage, for the hand of the LORD my God was on me.&rdquo; The narrative transitions from royal authorization to personal faith.</p>"
  }
}

